==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prisage
<hw>Pris"age</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>prisage</ets> a praising, valuing, taxing; cf. LL.
<ets>prisagium</ets> prisage; or from F. <ets>prise</ets> a taking,
capture, prize. See <er>Prize</er>.]</ety> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A right belonging to the crown of England, of taking
two tuns of wine from every ship importing twenty tuns or more, -- one
before and one behind the mast. By charter of Edward I. butlerage was
substituted for this.</def> <au>Blackstone.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The
share of merchandise taken as lawful prize at sea which belongs to the
king or admiral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Priscillianist</ent>⟦br⟧
